{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"af94af85-8d8f-42e3-ae32-59dd80a498a6","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2 / .NET 9.0** — here's the modern recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    public TestContext TestContext { get; set; } = null!;\n\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public void Setup()\n    {\n        // Synchronous init — runs before each test\n    }\n\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        // Async init — runs before each test\n        await Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void MyTest() { }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points for MSTest v3:**\n\n- **`TestContext`** — use a settable property (MSTest auto-injects it before each test).\n- **`[TestInitialize]`** — supports both `void` and `async Task`. You can have **one** per class; combine sync and async work inside it.\n- **`[ClassInitialize]`** / **`[ClassCleanup]`** — for one-time per-class setup (static methods).\n\nIf you need **both** sync and async work, the cleanest approach is a single async `[TestInitialize]`:\n\n```csharp\n[TestInitialize]\npublic async Task Setup()\n{\n    SyncSetup();                    // sync work\n    await AsyncSetup();             // async work\n}\n```\n\nWant me to scaffold a test class file for you?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a3e12bbb-7432-4d08-abd3-0f4244662c23","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. In modern MSTest (v3+), the recommended approach is:\n\n1. **TestContext injection**: Use a constructor parameter or a `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property. In MSTest v3+, constructor injection is supported.\n\n2. **Synchronous initialization**: Use `[TestInitialize]` method or constructor.\n\n3. **Asynchronous initialization**: Use `[TestInitialize]` with an async method (MSTest v2+ supports async TestInitialize).\n\nActually, in MSTest 3.6+, there's a newer pattern using `[ClassInitialize]` and `[ClassCleanup]` with lifecycle attributes. Let me provide the modern recommended patterns.\n\n\nSo for this version, I can inject TestContext as a property, use async methods in `[TestInitialize]`, and leverage constructor-based initialization for synchronous setup. I'll focus on the most practical patterns for their use case.","outputTokens":639},"id":"53d902b5-48dd-43f8-ad77-aad84f6f4887","timestamp":"2026-04-03T03:30:12.698Z","parentId":"1ad40c86-1251-4766-b22a-e5ec0fc0e641"}
